1
00:00:43,653 --> 00:00:46,404
Now here comes
the president's helicopter...

2
00:00:46,405 --> 00:00:48,022
...Marine Helicopter Number 1...

3
00:00:48,023 --> 00:00:52,368
...landing in the plaza on the east side
of the east front of the Capitol.

4
00:00:52,369 --> 00:00:56,539
The helicopter hovering gently
just off the ground.

5
00:00:56,540 --> 00:00:57,749
Amazing timing.

6
00:00:57,750 --> 00:01:00,335
The president flying
all the way across the world...

7
00:01:00,336 --> 00:01:03,838
...across the Atlantic Ocean,
arriving almost exactly...

8
00:01:03,839 --> 00:01:08,051
Exactly as scheduled,
at 9:30 in the Capitol plaza...

9
00:01:08,052 --> 00:01:11,137
...so he can go up the steps
of the House of Representatives...

10
00:01:11,138 --> 00:01:12,472
...go into the chamber...

11
00:01:12,473 --> 00:01:16,142
...and address the members of the House
and the Senate, Supreme Court...

12
00:01:16,143 --> 00:01:18,227
...the diplomatic corps of Washington...

13
00:01:18,228 --> 00:01:21,189
...all of whom are inside waiting for him
in the chamber.

14
00:01:21,190 --> 00:01:25,990
Mr. Speaker,
the president of the United States.

15
00:01:33,794 --> 00:01:37,054
And the president,
accompanied by the Escort Committee...

16
00:01:37,055 --> 00:01:41,855
...comes down the central aisle,
approaching the podium.

17
00:01:42,002 --> 00:01:43,836
He greets members of his cabinet...

18
00:01:43,837 --> 00:01:46,714
...and those who are waiting
to be confirmed as members...

19
00:01:46,715 --> 00:01:49,741
...as he reaches the rostrum.

20
00:01:51,637 --> 00:01:55,348
Shakes hands with the Speaker,
Carl Albert.

21
00:01:55,349 --> 00:01:58,016
A happy president, smiling.

22
00:01:58,769 --> 00:02:01,979
Ladies and gentlemen,
President Nixon will, in a moment...

23
00:02:01,980 --> 00:02:06,780
...address the Congress
and the people of the United States.

24
00:02:08,237 --> 00:02:10,185
Thank you.

25
00:04:05,521 --> 00:04:07,980
Car 727, Car 727.

26
00:04:07,981 --> 00:04:12,781
Open door at the Watergate office building.
Possible burglary. See the security guard.

27
00:04:12,945 --> 00:04:17,240
Are you sure you want us?
517 is closer, and they're in uniform.

28
00:04:17,241 --> 00:04:20,215
They're getting gas. You take it.

29
00:04:41,849 --> 00:04:44,720
Unit 1 to Unit 2.

30
00:04:45,727 --> 00:04:47,895
Unit 1 to Unit 2.

31
00:04:47,896 --> 00:04:51,538
- What?
- We're home.

32
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:10,509
Base 1 to Unit 1.

33
00:05:10,752 --> 00:05:12,962
Base 1 to Unit 1.

34
00:05:12,963 --> 00:05:15,590
We have some activity here.

35
00:05:15,591 --> 00:05:17,258
Silence is advised.

36
00:05:20,637 --> 00:05:22,534
Shut it off.

37
00:05:31,231 --> 00:05:33,774
Base 1 to Unit 1.

38
00:05:33,775 --> 00:05:36,493
Lights on the eighth floor.

39
00:05:36,612 --> 00:05:39,534
Base 1 to Unit 1.

40
00:05:39,990 --> 00:05:42,451
Is there anybody there?

41
00:05:47,748 --> 00:05:51,748
There's people, people on the balcony.
Armed people.

42
00:05:53,253 --> 00:05:56,022
Base 1 to Unit 1.

43
00:05:57,507 --> 00:06:01,969
Base 1 to Unit 1.
We may have some problems.

44
00:06:06,683 --> 00:06:09,042
Someone's here.

45
00:06:34,461 --> 00:06:35,896
Hold it, you...

46
00:06:36,213 --> 00:06:37,443
Police.

47
00:06:37,881 --> 00:06:40,086
Put your hands up.

48
00:06:50,227 --> 00:06:52,637
Drop that jacket.

49
00:06:54,064 --> 00:06:58,776
Walkie-talkie, two 35-mm cameras.

50
00:06:58,777 --> 00:07:03,406
Got it. That's good. All right, stay there.

51
00:07:03,407 --> 00:07:05,616
I got something for you. Did you see this?

52
00:07:05,617 --> 00:07:09,286
Couple sleeping in bed, car hits the house,
goes through their bedroom.

53
00:07:09,287 --> 00:07:12,999
Good morning. Crash.
Louis is over at Democratic headquarters.

54
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,800
One of the burglars had $814,
one $230, one $215, and one $234.

55
00:07:19,631 --> 00:07:24,176
Most of it was in $100 bills,
and in sequence.

56
00:07:24,177 --> 00:07:25,553
- Woodward?
- Yup.

57
00:07:25,554 --> 00:07:28,472
Break-in at Democratic headquarters.
There's been an arrest.

58
00:07:28,473 --> 00:07:30,975
- Local Democratic headquarters.
- Bugging the place.

59
00:07:30,976 --> 00:07:33,436
Check the time of arraignment
and get over there.

60
00:07:33,437 --> 00:07:36,480
And, Woodward,
it was National Democratic Headquarters.

61
00:07:36,481 --> 00:07:38,224
Right.

62
00:07:39,109 --> 00:07:41,444
- Anything else?
- Anything else?

63
00:07:41,445 --> 00:07:44,238
Break-in, car crash.
That's not bad for a Saturday.

64
00:07:44,239 --> 00:07:45,556
Let me know what happens.

65
00:07:45,557 --> 00:07:46,666
- Hello, Carl.
- Hi.

66
00:07:46,667 --> 00:07:48,075
Got anything on that couple?

67
00:07:48,076 --> 00:07:50,653
I know somebody on the staff at Watergate.
Want me...?

68
00:07:50,654 --> 00:07:53,681
Why don't you finish one story
before trying to get on another?

69
00:07:53,682 --> 00:07:55,374
I finished it.

70
00:07:55,375 --> 00:07:57,752
- The Virginia Legislature story?
- I finished it.

71
00:07:57,753 --> 00:07:59,587
All right, give it to me.

72
00:07:59,588 --> 00:08:01,338
I'm just polishing it.

73
00:08:01,339 --> 00:08:06,007
- I'll work the phones.
- Polishing it. Yeah, you work the phones.

74
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:09,055
- Who cares?
- What about property damage?

75
00:08:09,056 --> 00:08:11,223
Sorry, who are the lawy...?
Excuse me, sorry.

76
00:08:11,224 --> 00:08:14,268
Who are the lawyers
for the five men arrested at Watergate?

77
00:08:14,269 --> 00:08:16,854
- Do you know?
- Well, these two were assigned to it.

78
00:08:16,855 --> 00:08:18,064
Sorry?

79
00:08:18,065 --> 00:08:20,274
These two were appointed to the case.

80
00:08:20,275 --> 00:08:23,244
Only now it turns out
the burglars have their own counsel.

81
00:08:23,245 --> 00:08:25,654
- The burglars have their own counsel?
- Right.

82
00:08:25,655 --> 00:08:29,658
- That's kind of unusual, wouldn't you say?
- For burglars it's unusual.

83
00:08:29,659 --> 00:08:31,452
Do you know the name of the counsel?

84
00:08:31,453 --> 00:08:33,621
I don't know. Some country-club type.

85
00:08:33,622 --> 00:08:36,332
You are charged
with soliciting prostitution...

86
00:08:36,333 --> 00:08:39,210
...at 14th and U Streets Northwest.

87
00:08:42,881 --> 00:08:46,050
Your Honor,
Mr. Socket has in the past been reliable...

88
00:08:46,051 --> 00:08:48,677
...for court appearances when ordered.

89
00:08:48,678 --> 00:08:51,555
I think $300
would subsequently be suggested....

90
00:08:51,556 --> 00:08:54,223
Excuse me, what is your name?

91
00:08:54,893 --> 00:08:58,534
I'm Bob Woodward
of the Washington Post.

92
00:08:58,772 --> 00:09:00,648
- Markham.
- Markham?

93
00:09:00,649 --> 00:09:05,162
Mr. Markham, are you here in connection
with the Watergate burglary?

94
00:09:05,237 --> 00:09:07,544
I'm not here.

95
00:09:09,950 --> 00:09:11,743
Okay.

96
00:09:13,537 --> 00:09:15,955
Well, clearly, I am here...

97
00:09:15,956 --> 00:09:19,375
...but only as an individual,
not as the attorney of record.

98
00:09:19,376 --> 00:09:21,335
Who is?

99
00:09:21,336 --> 00:09:23,899
Mr. Starkey.

100
00:09:24,047 --> 00:09:26,465
- Do you have any kind of...?
- Whatever you want...

101
00:09:26,466 --> 00:09:28,342
...you'll have to get from him.

102
00:09:28,343 --> 00:09:30,958
I have nothing more to say.

103
00:09:39,855 --> 00:09:41,957
Uh, Starkey. S-T....

104
00:09:46,403 --> 00:09:47,903
Mr. Starkey was very helpful.

105
00:09:47,904 --> 00:09:52,199
Four Cuban-Americans and another man,
James W. McCord.

106
00:09:52,200 --> 00:09:55,369
Look, I told you inside,
I have nothing more to say.

107
00:09:55,370 --> 00:09:57,729
I understand that.

108
00:09:57,747 --> 00:10:01,208
What I don't understand
is how you got here.

109
00:10:01,209 --> 00:10:04,753
I assure you
there's nothing very mysterious involved.

110
00:10:04,754 --> 00:10:07,214
Well, I was talking
to a couple of the lawyers...

111
00:10:07,215 --> 00:10:09,466
...assigned to represent the burglars.

112
00:10:09,467 --> 00:10:10,676
So?

113
00:10:10,677 --> 00:10:13,262
They never would've been assigned
to the burglars...

114
00:10:13,263 --> 00:10:16,557
...had anyone known the burglars
had arranged for their own counsel.

115
00:10:16,558 --> 00:10:18,976
The burglars couldn't have
arranged their counsel.

116
00:10:18,977 --> 00:10:21,540
They never even made a phone call.

117
00:10:21,813 --> 00:10:25,608
So if no one asked you to be here,
why are you here?

118
00:10:25,609 --> 00:10:28,152
- Don't take this personally, Mr....
- Woodward.

119
00:10:28,153 --> 00:10:32,114
Woodward.
It would be a mistake to do that.

120
00:10:32,115 --> 00:10:33,750
I just don't have anything to say.

121
00:10:37,454 --> 00:10:40,748
Your Honor, Mr. Betts
is a young man with no prior record.

122
00:10:40,749 --> 00:10:45,549
The defense has suggested a release
on personal bond.

123
00:10:45,837 --> 00:10:50,094
Did one of the other men
involved in the break-in call you?

124
00:10:50,800 --> 00:10:54,053
What reason do you have to assume
there were other people involved?

125
00:10:54,054 --> 00:10:56,847
One of your clients was arrested
with a walkie-talkie.

126
00:10:56,848 --> 00:10:59,934
They're not my clients.

127
00:10:59,935 --> 00:11:04,104
- I don't wanna talk about this anymore.
- You're a lawyer and you're here.

128
00:11:04,105 --> 00:11:08,905
Well, uh, one of the defendants, Mr. Barker,
and I met at a social occasion once.

129
00:11:09,653 --> 00:11:11,498
Where?

130
00:11:11,529 --> 00:11:14,198
- I have nothing else to say.
- A Miami social occasion?

131
00:11:14,199 --> 00:11:17,743
Mr. Starkey says the Cubans
were from Miami.

132
00:11:17,744 --> 00:11:21,497
L-62, James McCord.
L-63, Bernard Barker.

133
00:11:21,498 --> 00:11:24,333
L-64, Virgilio Gonzalez.

134
00:11:24,334 --> 00:11:26,669
L-65, Eugenio Martinez.

135
00:11:26,670 --> 00:11:29,588
L-66, Frank Sturgis.

136
00:11:29,589 --> 00:11:34,389
Please step forward, Attorney Starkey.
All charged with burglary two.

137
00:11:36,513 --> 00:11:39,556
- And, Mr. Starkey, you represent all five?
- Yes, Your Honor.

138
00:11:39,557 --> 00:11:42,977
And are all five gentlemen charged
with burglary in the second degree?

139
00:11:42,978 --> 00:11:44,186
Yes, Your Honor.

140
00:11:44,187 --> 00:11:46,981
Your names, please,
and state your professions.

141
00:11:46,982 --> 00:11:50,693
Bernard Barker, anti-Communist.

142
00:11:50,694 --> 00:11:55,494
Anti-Communist?
That, sir, is not your average profession.

143
00:11:57,284 --> 00:12:00,536
McCORD:
James McCord, security consultant.

144
00:12:00,537 --> 00:12:01,829
Where?

145
00:12:01,830 --> 00:12:05,124
McCORD:
Government. Uh, recently retired.

146
00:12:05,125 --> 00:12:07,042
Where in the government?

147
00:12:07,043 --> 00:12:09,378
McCORD:
Central Intelligence Agency.

148
00:12:09,379 --> 00:12:10,713
Where?

149
00:12:10,714 --> 00:12:12,611
McCORD: The CIA.

150
00:12:12,882 --> 00:12:16,510
Sturgis, Frank A., salvage operator.

151
00:12:16,511 --> 00:12:18,971
Holy shit.

152
00:12:18,972 --> 00:12:21,890
Eugenio Martinez,
known as Gene Valdez.

153
00:12:21,891 --> 00:12:24,226
James W. McCord, alias Edward Martin.

154
00:12:24,227 --> 00:12:28,105
Frank Sturgis, alias Frank Fiorini.
All five of the men had at least one alias.

155
00:12:28,106 --> 00:12:30,983
Any proof they were trying
to bug the Democratic chairman?

156
00:12:30,984 --> 00:12:32,693
It's obvious they were trying to.

157
00:12:32,694 --> 00:12:35,237
They wouldn't go to that trouble
to bug secretaries.

158
00:12:35,238 --> 00:12:37,906
- There's no proof.
- I called a lawyer in Miami I know.

159
00:12:37,907 --> 00:12:40,868
He said four of the guys that were arrested
were from Miami.

160
00:12:40,869 --> 00:12:42,661
Gonzalez, Martinez, Sturgis and, uh....

161
00:12:42,662 --> 00:12:43,871
- Barker.
- Yeah, Barker.

162
00:12:43,872 --> 00:12:46,707
And all four of them were involved
in CIA activities and...

163
00:12:46,708 --> 00:12:48,334
- No, only one.
- Yeah, and they...

164
00:12:48,335 --> 00:12:51,795
No, only one of them was admitted CIA,
and the CIA won't confirm that.

165
00:12:51,796 --> 00:12:53,922
In fact, they deny even knowing McCord.

166
00:12:53,923 --> 00:12:56,759
But it's obvious
that with all that money and equipment...

167
00:12:56,760 --> 00:13:00,012
...they weren't out to, you know,
work by themselves.

168
00:13:00,013 --> 00:13:01,221
Somebody hired them.

169
00:13:01,222 --> 00:13:03,766
I'm interested in what you know.

170
00:13:03,767 --> 00:13:06,727
We don't know why they wanted
to bug Democratic headquarters.

171
00:13:06,728 --> 00:13:10,397
Whether they were working for themselves,
other individuals, organizations.

172
00:13:10,398 --> 00:13:12,316
Could be a story or just crazy Cubans.

173
00:13:12,317 --> 00:13:14,485
Bachinski, when you get there,
take it easy.

174
00:13:14,486 --> 00:13:16,536
The police are nervous.

175
00:13:25,121 --> 00:13:27,790
- Yeah?
- Calling from police headquarters.

176
00:13:27,791 --> 00:13:31,418
A friend just showed me what they found
in the hotel rooms of the burglars.

177
00:13:31,419 --> 00:13:33,587
There's something
you might wanna look into.

178
00:13:33,588 --> 00:13:35,130
Hang on.

179
00:13:35,131 --> 00:13:36,298
Okay, go ahead.

180
00:13:36,299 --> 00:13:39,343
There's a strange entry
in two of the burglars' address books.

181
00:13:39,344 --> 00:13:43,263
- Yeah?
- One says "H.H. at W.H."

182
00:13:43,264 --> 00:13:46,495
The other says
"Howard Hunt, W. House."

183
00:13:49,771 --> 00:13:52,064
You can dial the White House direct,
can't you?

184
00:13:52,065 --> 00:13:53,899
- Yeah.
- What's the number?

185
00:13:53,900 --> 00:13:58,700
456-1414.

186
00:14:07,747 --> 00:14:10,833
- White House.
- Howard Hunt, please.

187
00:14:10,834 --> 00:14:13,085
Mr. Hunt isn't here just now.

188
00:14:13,086 --> 00:14:16,839
He might be in Mr. Colson's office.
I'll connect you.

189
00:14:16,840 --> 00:14:18,890
Thank you.

190
00:14:19,008 --> 00:14:21,635
- Charles Colson's office.
- Howard Hunt, please.

191
00:14:21,636 --> 00:14:23,679
Mr. Hunt isn't here just now.

192
00:14:23,680 --> 00:14:26,974
- Do you know when he'll be back?
- No, I don't.

193
00:14:26,975 --> 00:14:28,183
Okay, thank you.

194
00:14:28,184 --> 00:14:30,727
- Have you tried the Mullen firm?
- I beg your pardon?

195
00:14:30,728 --> 00:14:33,897
He also works as a writer
at Mullen and Company Public Relations.

196
00:14:33,898 --> 00:14:37,818
- You have a phone on that or an address?
- No, I don't. I'm sorry.

197
00:14:37,819 --> 00:14:39,510
All right, thank you.

198
00:14:39,988 --> 00:14:42,948
Do you know
in a survey taken, 10.9 percent...?

199
00:14:42,949 --> 00:14:44,744
Harry.

200
00:14:44,868 --> 00:14:46,661
Who's Charles Colson?

201
00:14:48,163 --> 00:14:50,372
Who's Charles Colson?

202
00:14:50,373 --> 00:14:52,219
Sit down.

203
00:14:52,709 --> 00:14:54,668
I'm glad you asked me that question.

204
00:14:54,669 --> 00:14:58,005
The reason I'm glad is because
if you had asked Simons or Bradlee...

205
00:14:58,006 --> 00:14:59,214
...they would've said:

206
00:14:59,215 --> 00:15:03,385
"You know, we're gonna have to fire this
schmuck at once because he's so dumb."

207
00:15:03,386 --> 00:15:05,077
Who is Charles Colson?

208
00:15:05,972 --> 00:15:09,600
The most powerful man
in the United States is President Nixon.

209
00:15:09,601 --> 00:15:11,292
You've heard of him?

210
00:15:12,687 --> 00:15:15,981
Charles Colson is special counsel
to the president.

211
00:15:15,982 --> 00:15:18,495
There's a cartoon on his wall.

212
00:15:18,526 --> 00:15:22,154
Caption reads,
"When you've got them by the balls...

213
00:15:22,155 --> 00:15:24,239
...their hearts and minds will follow."

214
00:15:24,240 --> 00:15:26,907
Do you have a list of receipts?

215
00:15:27,285 --> 00:15:30,662
Hello, Mr. Murray?
This is Ivy Mills of the Washington Post.

216
00:15:30,663 --> 00:15:31,914
I'd like to know if....

217
00:15:31,915 --> 00:15:33,081
Mullen and Company.

218
00:15:33,082 --> 00:15:36,460
- Howard Hunt, please.
- One moment, please.

219
00:15:36,461 --> 00:15:38,665
Howard Hunt here.

220
00:15:39,214 --> 00:15:41,924
Hi, I'm Bob Woodward
of the Washington Post.

221
00:15:41,925 --> 00:15:44,176
Yes. Yes, what is it?

222
00:15:44,177 --> 00:15:46,845
I was just wondering
why your name and phone number...

223
00:15:46,846 --> 00:15:50,724
...were in the address books
of two of the men arrested at Watergate.

224
00:15:50,725 --> 00:15:52,314
Good God.

225
00:15:52,894 --> 00:15:55,771
- Do you care to comment?
- The matter is under adjudication.

226
00:15:55,772 --> 00:15:57,874
I have no comment.

227
00:15:59,484 --> 00:16:01,109
- Hello?
- This is Bob Woodward...

228
00:16:01,110 --> 00:16:02,486
...of the Washington Post.

229
00:16:02,487 --> 00:16:05,864
I was told that you had worked
with a Mr. Howard Hunt.

230
00:16:05,865 --> 00:16:07,454
Why would anyone say that?

231
00:16:07,951 --> 00:16:09,785
You do know Mr. Hunt?

232
00:16:09,786 --> 00:16:11,119
No, I don't believe so...

233
00:16:11,120 --> 00:16:13,622
...and I can't imagine
why anyone would say that.

234
00:16:13,623 --> 00:16:16,416
I'm really sorry, but I was on my way out.
Goodbye.

235
00:16:16,417 --> 00:16:21,187
Could we just confirm a couple...? Bye.

236
00:16:22,799 --> 00:16:24,967
Did you say the Washington Post?

237
00:16:24,968 --> 00:16:26,510
Yes, that's right, the Post.

238
00:16:26,511 --> 00:16:28,971
Your publishing firm
was listed in some papers...

239
00:16:28,972 --> 00:16:30,806
...in connection with a Howard Hunt.

240
00:16:30,807 --> 00:16:35,477
Yeah. Yeah, he's one of our authors.
He wrote spy novels, I think.

241
00:16:35,478 --> 00:16:38,855
What type of spy novels were they?
Were they modern or period...?

242
00:16:38,856 --> 00:16:41,525
You say "wrote"?
You mean he's no longer with you?

243
00:16:41,526 --> 00:16:42,734
No, not at this time.

244
00:16:42,735 --> 00:16:45,445
How long has it been
since you heard from him?

245
